1. $S_{11}$ : Input Reflection (Return Loss)
What it means: The signal is injected into Port 1, and the VNA measures what bounces back into Port 1.
What it tests: Impedance matching. If your LNA has a perfect $50\ \Omega$ input, $S_{11}$ will be a very large negative number (e.g., -20 dB), meaning almost nothing reflected back. If the cable is broken or the chip is badly designed, $S_{11}$ will be close to 0 dB, meaning the signal hit a wall and bounced right back.
2. $S_{21}$ : Forward Transmission (Gain or Insertion Loss)
What it means: The signal is injected into Port 1, travels through the Device Under Test (DUT), and the VNA measures what comes out at Port 2.
What it tests: What the component actually "does" to the signal.
For an LNA, $S_{21}$ is your Gain (e.g., +15 dB).
For a Filter or Splitter, $S_{21}$ is your Insertion Loss (e.g., -2 dB).
3. $S_{12}$ : Reverse Transmission (Isolation)
What it means: The VNA switches directions. It injects a signal into Port 2 (the output of your LNA) and measures what leaks backwards through the device out of Port 1.
What it tests: Isolation. Amplifiers are supposed to be one-way streets. A good LNA will heavily block signals trying to go backward, resulting in a very low $S_{12}$ (e.g., -40 dB). If $S_{12}$ gets too high, the amplifier can turn into an oscillator and become unstable.
4. $S_{22}$ : Output Reflection (Output Return Loss)
What it means: The signal is injected into Port 2, and the VNA measures what bounces back into Port 2.
What it tests: Output impedance matching. Just like the input, the output of your LNA needs to be matched to $50\ \Omega$ so it can seamlessly pass the amplified signal to the next stage (like a Mixer) without reflections.


